A man on parole for attempted murder was arrested Wednesday for allegedly slashing a commuter in the face in an unprovoked attack at an Upper Manhattan subway station, sources said. Leoanel Medina, 30, was busted by cops in Manhattan who recognized his face from a wanted poster stemming from a Tuesday attack at the 168th Street-Washington Heights No. 1 train station around 6:30 p.m., law enforcement sources said. Medina is accused of slashing a 27-year-old man in the face on the stationâ€™s mezzanine, according to police and sources. The victim was taken to Harlem Hospital in stable condition. Medina was charged with assault. He is on parole for attempted murder after slashing a victim several times in Washington Heights in 2013, sources said. Additional reporting by Kenneth Garger